# Noma — Direction and Positioning

::summary
This document is the canonical statement of what Noma is, what it is not,
and how to evaluate every proposed feature. It refines the original vision
in `PLAN.md` with the post-MVP positioning (PLAN.md §23). Everything here
is itself written in Noma — the rendered HTML version is what you'd send
to a collaborator who has never heard of the project.
::

## The one-liner

::callout{tone="tip"}
**Noma is proof-before-apply docs for AI agents.**
::

## The longer version

> Noma is a plain-text source format for AI-maintained documents in Git. It
> keeps source readable, gives agents scoped context and stable block IDs,
> generates a proof before patches are applied, and renders polished artifacts
> for human review.

## The proof loop

::grid{columns=4}
:::card{title="1 · Source" icon="source"}
Readable text in Git, with stable IDs on the blocks agents may touch.
:::

:::card{title="2 · Context" icon="agent"}
Scoped LLM output and an ID registry, instead of dumping whole docs into prompts.
:::

:::card{title="3 · Proof" icon="review"}
Dry-run patches with validation, hashes, source preservation, diff, and preview.
:::

:::card{title="4 · Artifact" icon="artifact"}
The approved source renders to HTML, PDF, DOCX, JSON, Markdown, or static Spaces.
:::
::

## The central design test

::decision{id="design-test" status="accepted"}
Every feature must answer **yes** to all four:

1. Can a human understand this in raw text?
2. Can an agent inspect enough scoped context to choose a narrow edit?
3. Can Noma prove the patch before source is written?
4. Can it render into an artifact people actually want to read?

If any answer is "no", the feature does not belong in core Noma.
::

## Why not Markdown

::claim{id="claim-vs-markdown" confidence=0.85 noverify}
Markdown is excellent as lightweight prose, but it is too weak for
modern AI-era documents. It has no native layout, no semantic blocks,
no validation, no agent patch model, and no clean LLM export.
::

| Need                   | Markdown                | Noma                 |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------- | -------------------- |
| Plain-text readability | Excellent               | Excellent            |
| Git diffs              | Excellent               | Excellent            |
| Grids/cards/tabs       | Poor                    | Native               |
| Charts/plots           | Poor                    | Native               |
| Semantic blocks        | Weak                    | Native               |
| Claims/evidence/risks  | Ad hoc                  | Native               |
| Agent patching         | Weak                    | Native block IDs     |
| Validation             | Weak                    | Built-in             |
| Book scale             | Possible but fragmented | Native project model |
| Beautiful web output   | Needs tooling           | Built-in             |
| LLM context export     | Basic                   | Structured           |

## Why not raw HTML

::claim{id="claim-vs-html" confidence=0.88 noverify}
HTML is excellent as a rendering target, but unpleasant as long-term
source. It is noisy in Git diffs, fragile under agent edits, awkward
for book-scale authoring, and requires custom tooling for every
validation rule.
::

| Need                      | Raw HTML   | Noma                   |
| ------------------------- | ---------- | ---------------------- |
| Browser rendering         | Excellent  | Excellent via renderer |
| Human source readability  | Poor       | Excellent              |
| Long-term maintainability | Poor       | Strong                 |
| Git diffs                 | Noisy      | Clean                  |
| Book authoring            | Awkward    | Native                 |
| PDF/EPUB export           | Awkward    | Native targets         |
| Semantic reasoning blocks | Ad hoc     | Native                 |
| Agent-safe edits          | Fragile    | Block-level operations |
| LLM export                | Noisy      | Clean                  |
| Styling consistency       | Manual CSS | Themes                 |
| Validation                | Custom     | Built-in               |
| Reusable components       | Possible   | Declarative            |

## Why not LaTeX

::claim{id="claim-vs-latex" confidence=0.8 noverify}
LaTeX is excellent for publication-grade typesetting and equation-heavy
papers, but it is a poor default collaboration surface for agent-maintained
artifacts that need live diagnostics, semantic patch targets, table/data
editing, and multi-format context export.
::

| Need                         | LaTeX                    | Noma                         |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------ | ---------------------------- |
| Publication typography       | Excellent                | Export target, not core goal |
| Equations                    | Excellent                | Supported via math blocks    |
| Compiler/debug loop          | Heavy                    | Parser + validator feedback  |
| Visual table/data editing    | External tooling         | Workbench grid + patch ops   |
| Agent-safe edits             | Fragile without tooling  | Block-level operations       |
| HTML/LLM artifact generation | Extra pipeline           | Native render targets        |
| Source-control readability   | Strong for TeX experts   | Designed for mixed teams     |

## Five v1 pillars

::grid{columns=2}
:::card{title="1 · Markdown-compatible prose"}
`# headings`, `**bold**`, lists, links, fenced code work without
ceremony. Reduces adoption friction.
:::

:::card{title="2 · Directive blocks"}
`::type{key="value"} ... ::` is the universal extension mechanism.
Examples: `callout`, `claim`, `evidence`, `decision`.
:::

:::card{title="3 · Layout blocks"}
`grid`, `columns`, `card`, `tabs`, `accordion`, `sidebar`, `hero`,
`section`, `callout`. Semantic layout, not CSS.
:::

:::card{title="4 · Data + visualization"}
`dataset`, `plot`, `metric`, `table`. HTML renderer makes them
interactive; PDF static; LLM summarizes.
:::
::

::card{title="5 · Agent collaboration"}
`agent_task`, `instruction`, `review`, `todo`, `decision`, `claim`,
`evidence`, `risk`, `assumption`, `open_question`, `change_request`.
Agent-native from day one.
::

## GitHub-first adoption

The first market is Git-based teams whose docs, specs, ADRs, runbooks, and
research memos are already being touched by AI agents. The product promise is
not "a better wiki." It is:

```bash
noma ids docs/api.noma
noma render docs/api.noma --to llm --select claim,evidence,risk --budget 12000
noma proof docs/api.noma --ops proposed-docs-patch.json --out dist/api-proof.html
noma check docs/api.noma --profile technical-docs
```

The reviewer should see which blocks changed, which IDs were targeted, whether
references still validate, what rendered preview changed, and whether any
warnings remain before the patch is applied or merged.

## Artifact rendering

A `.noma` source can render into:

- a report
- a spec
- a research memo
- a dashboard
- a landing page
- a prototype
- a code-review explainer
- a book chapter
- a searchable documentation space
- a project plan
- a decision record
- a Word-compatible review handoff
- a custom mini-tool

```bash
noma render pr-review.noma --to html --strict --out pr-review.html
```

Output: a single `.html` artifact that opens locally or uploads anywhere. Use `--strict` for team-published artifacts that should block unsafe escape hatches and external runtimes.

## Noma Spaces

::claim{id="claim-noma-spaces" confidence=0.86 noverify}
Noma can be a better documentation manager than a wiki when the source must stay
reviewable, portable, and safe for agents to maintain.
::

A book manifest can render to a static Noma Space:

```bash
noma render docs/book.noma.yml --to site --out dist/docs
```

That output gives teams the useful surface of a shared documentation system:
multi-page navigation, search, page metadata, related pages, backlinks, copy
links, print output, and a root JSON search index that agents can inspect.
Static Spaces remain the durable publishing artifact when a team wants Git as
the collaboration system.

The hosted path is **Noma Cloud**, but it should follow CLI/CI adoption rather
than lead it. Cloud is the place for hosted proof archives, rendered spaces,
permissions, search, and review surfaces once teams already trust Noma in Git.
A cloud space opens in `cloud.html`, carries multiple editable pages, enforces
viewer/editor/owner controls, supports user invites and share links, renders
reader artifacts at `/d/<id>` and `/s/<id>`, and deploys to a user-owned VPS
with EZKeel. The hosted layer persists workspace data in SQLite and exposes a
bounded `/api/db/query` endpoint for documents, spaces, blocks, and users.

This is the natural shape for documentation, internal books, research papers,
architecture records, onboarding guides, and long-lived agent memory packs: a
readable source tree, a reader-facing space, and patchable IDs for every future
agent edit.

