## Themes, not inline styling

::callout{tone="warning"}
**Avoid:** `::card{padding="24px" border="1px solid #ddd" shadow="large"}`
The source becomes unreadable and the document loses portability.
::

::callout{tone="tip"}
**Prefer:** `::card{variant="important"}`
The theme decides how `important` renders. Source stays clean,
artifacts stay consistent.
::

## Escape hatches

Allowed but not default. Reserved for cases that would otherwise force a
worse compromise.

```noma
::html
<div>Raw HTML only when absolutely necessary.</div>
::

::svg
<svg>...</svg>
::
```

Rules:

- allowed only in artifact mode
- excluded or summarized in LLM mode
- flagged by validator if unsafe
- disabled by default in trusted publishing contexts

## Core directives vs. community packs

::decision{id="core-directive-boundary" status="proposed"}
Core Noma absorbs directives that are **shape-stable, domain-neutral, and useful in more than one downstream renderer**. Domain-specific shapes (finance positions, ops incidents, lab notebooks) belong in **namespaced community packs**, not the core surface.
::

**Why a boundary at all.** The validator and HTML renderer hardcode rules per directive name. Every accepted core directive is a forever-supported shape — it cannot be removed without breaking documents that already use it. A growing surface area also makes the format harder to learn and harder to write tools for.

**Core today (research-shaped).** `claim`, `evidence`, `counterevidence`, `assumption`, `risk`, `hypothesis`, `result`, `limitation`, `open_question`, `decision`, `adr`, `dataset`, `plot`, `metric`, `agent_task`, `todo`, `review`, `comment`, `change_request`, `provenance`, `confidence`, `citation`, `state_change`. These are kept because *any* knowledge-work document benefits from them — a roadmap and a research thesis both need claims, risks, and decisions.

**Out of core (proposed packs).**

| Pack name   | Sample directives                                       | Owner pattern          |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| `finance::` | `position`, `trade`, `forecast`, `holding`, `pnl_event` | finance/portfolio docs |
| `ops::`     | `incident`, `runbook`, `postmortem`, `alert`, `oncall`  | SRE/ops teams          |
| `lab::`     | `experiment`, `protocol`, `sample`, `apparatus`         | wet/dry-lab notebooks  |
| `legal::`   | `clause`, `obligation`, `party`, `jurisdiction`         | contract drafting      |

**Pack contract.**

1. **Namespacing.** Pack directive names use `pack::name` (e.g. `::finance::position{...}`). The core parser accepts namespaced directive names; full renderer/validator plug-in loading is still future work.
2. **Renderer plug-in.** Packs ship a function `render(node, ctx) → string` that the core HTML renderer falls back to when it sees an unknown directive name with a registered prefix.
3. **Validator plug-in.** Same shape for validator rules — packs export `validate(node) → Diagnostic[]` for their owned namespace.
4. **No reserved attribute names.** Packs may not redefine `id`, `variant`, `noverify`, `for`, or any attribute the core validator already inspects.
5. **Profile compatibility.** Pack directives are out-of-profile by default. Documents declaring built-in profiles such as `technical-docs`, `research-memo`, `adr`, `spec`, or `minimal` will warn on pack usage; pack consumers should declare `profile: <pack>` (or omit profile entirely).

**Promotion rule.** A pack directive can be promoted to core if (a) two unrelated packs converge on the same shape, or (b) a renderer/validator rule in the pack would benefit every Noma document. Promotion is a versioned change that ships in a minor release.

This stance means the core stays small, the validator's per-block rule set stays bounded, and the ecosystem can grow without forcing every downstream tool to switch over a sprawling union.

## What NOT to build (yet)

::risk{id="scope-creep" severity="high" owner="ferax564"}
The following are out of scope for v1. Each one would slow the format
work that matters more.

- visual / WYSIWYG editor
- realtime collaboration
- plugin marketplace
- enterprise auth/permissions
- multi-tenant enterprise cloud platform
- complex CSS theming engine
- a Markdown-to-Noma converter (Noma → Markdown is the supported direction)
::

